From: Gilly1970 <gilroyscott@hotmail.com>
Subject: [PATCH] wifi: mt76: mt7996: stop tx_free parse at buffer edge on bad MSDU_CNT

mt7996: handle truncated PKT_TYPE_TXRX_NOTIFY descriptors from AN7581 NPU

The Airoha AN7581 NPU occasionally emits tx_free descriptors where
MT_TXFREE0_MSDU_CNT exceeds the number of MSDUs actually DMA'd. The
loop trusts the header count, hits the buffer boundary, and fires
WARN_ON_ONCE - a noisy splat for a firmware quirk we cannot fix in the
driver.

In all observed cases the parser stops exactly at the skb boundary
(over_by=0), so no out-of-bounds read occurs. Stop cleanly at the real
buffer edge with `break` rather than `return`, so txwi/skbs already
collected before the truncation are still released and tx queues remain
unblocked.

The condition is benign and self-healing, so demote the notice to
pr_debug: it stays observable via dynamic debug when investigating, but
produces no log output (no alarming warning) in a normal build.

---
 mt7996/mac.c | 7 +++++--
 1 file changed, 5 insertions(+), 2 deletions(-)

diff --git a/mt7996/mac.c b/mt7996/mac.c
index 367b51a..bda0afa 100644
--- a/mt7996/mac.c
+++ b/mt7996/mac.c
@@ -1312,8 +1312,11 @@ mt7996_mac_tx_free(struct mt7996_dev *dev, void *data, int len)
 		u32 msdu, info;
 		u8 i;
 
-		if (WARN_ON_ONCE((void *)cur_info >= end))
-			return;
+		if ((void *)cur_info >= end) {
+			pr_debug("mt7996: tx_free truncated, count=%u total=%u len=%d ver=%u\n",
+				 count, total, len, ver);
+			break;
+		}
 		/* 1'b1: new wcid pair.
 		 * 1'b0: msdu_id with the same 'wcid pair' as above.
 		 */
-- 
2.43.0

